s:12:\"free plugins\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=540655\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:592:\"<p>Are you trying to keep your website safe? Using a security tool on your WordPress site is essential to having a successful business online. In this post, we&#8217;ve rounded up the very best WordPress security plugins to protect your website in 2019. Do I Need a WordPress Security Plugin? If you&#8217;re asking yourself are WordPress [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/best-wordpress-security-plugins/\">7 Best WordPress Security Plugins to Protect Your Website (2019)</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12:\"Lisa Gennaro\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:18426:\"<p>Are you trying to keep your website safe?</p>\n<p>Using a security tool on your WordPress site is essential to having a successful business online.</p>\n<p>In this post, we&#8217;ve rounded up the very best WordPress security plugins to protect your website in 2019.</p>\n<h3>Do I Need a WordPress Security Plugin?</h3>\n<p>If you&#8217;re asking yourself are WordPress security plugins necessary? Know this stat — The average website is attacked <strong>44 times every day</strong>.</p>\n<p>And if any of those attacks are successful, it could seriously hurt your business online.</p>\n<p>That&#8217;s why your <a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/wordpress-security/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">WordPress site security</a> and online security measures should be at the top of your priorities.</p>\n<p>Some of the negative things that can happen with a security breach include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Online criminals can steal the data belonging to you and your customers</li>\n<li>Private data from your business and your customers could be exposed</li>\n<li>Your website content can be completely deleted</li>\n<li>Your site could distribute malware to your visitors hurting your brand and SEO rankings</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/beginners-step-step-guide-fixing-hacked-wordpress-site/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Fixing your hacked WordPress site</a> can be a complicated and costly process</li>\n</ul>\n<p>All of these reasons make having a WordPress security plugin installed on your site incredibly important.</p>\n<p>So now that you know the risks of an unsecured website and the reasons why you need a WordPress security plugin, let&#8217;s talk about the top choices.</p>\n<p>This list of the best WordPress security plugin in 2019 should help you pick which one works best for you and your business.</p>\n<h3>What Is the Best WordPress Security Plugin in 2019?</h3>\n<p>So which WordPress security plugin is best for you? Let&#8217;s take a peek at the list:</p>\n<h3>1. <a title=\"Sucuri\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/sucuri/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Sucuri</a></h3>\n<p><a title=\"Sucuri\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/sucuri/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-512215\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/sucuri-best-cdn-provider-to-speed-up-your-website.png\" alt=\"best free wordpress security plugin\" width=\"1116\" height=\"489\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/sucuri-best-cdn-provider-to-speed-up-your-website.png 1116w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/sucuri-best-cdn-provider-to-speed-up-your-website-300x131.png 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/sucuri-best-cdn-provider-to-speed-up-your-website-768x337.png 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/sucuri-best-cdn-provider-to-speed-up-your-website-1024x449.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1116px) 100vw, 1116px\" /></a></p>\n<p>The best free WordPress security plugin available today is Sucuri. The all-in-one security platform is wildly popular for good reason.</p>\n<p>Although <a title=\"Sucuri\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/sucuri/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Sucuri</a> is a great free WordPress security plugin for websites, the pro version is actually the real must-have.</p>\n<p><strong>Features:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>They&#8217;ll clean up your WordPress site at no additional cost if it gets malware</li>\n<li>Firewall protection helps you block brute force and malicious attacks from accessing your WordPress site</li>\n<li>Lets you conduct malware scanning</li>\n<li>Keeps track of everything that happens on your site, including file changes, last logins, and failed login attempts</li>\n<li>Can reduce server load time and improve your site’s performance by blocking malicious traffic</li>\n<li>Serves static content from their own <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/best-cdn-providers/\">CDN servers</a></li>\n<li>Protects your website against SQL Injections, XSS, and all known attacks</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong></p>\n<p>There&#8217;s a free version of Sucuri and the Pro version is $299/year.</p>\n<p><a title=\"Sucuri\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/sucuri/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Click here to get started with Sucuri today</a>.</p>\n<h3>2. <a title=\"iThemes Security\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/ithemes-security/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">iThemes Security Pro</a></h3>\n<p><a title=\"iThemes Security\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/ithemes-security/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-540660\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/ithemes-security-pro-wordpress-sites.png\" alt=\"ithemes security pro wordpress sites\" width=\"1116\" height=\"452\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/ithemes-security-pro-wordpress-sites.png 1116w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/ithemes-security-pro-wordpress-sites-300x122.png 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/ithemes-security-pro-wordpress-sites-768x311.png 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/ithemes-security-pro-wordpress-sites-1024x415.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1116px) 100vw, 1116px\" /></a></p>\n<p>If you&#8217;re a WordPress user, you might be familiar with the team that created <a title=\"iThemes Security\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/ithemes-security/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">iThemes Security Pro</a> since they also built the popular <a title=\"BackupBuddy\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/backupbuddy/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">BackupBuddy</a> plugin. All of their tools offer an easy-to-use interface for brute force security protection and more.</p>\n<p><strong>Features:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Two-factor authentication for an extra layer of security</li>\n<li>Powerful password enforcement</li>\n<li>404 detection and plugin scans</li>\n<li>Scheduled <a href=\"https://www.isitwp.com/best-wordpress-backup-plugins-compared/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">WordPress backups</a></li>\n<li>Locks out any suspicious IP that scans for vulnerabilities on your site</li>\n<li>Sends email alerts to notify you of any recent file updates on your site that may be malicious</li>\n<li>Ability to limit login attempts</li>\n<li>Although there&#8217;s no website firewall or malware scanner, they do use <a title=\"Sucuri\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/sucuri/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Sucuri</a>&#8216;s Sitecheck malware scanner</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong></p>\n<p>iThemes Security Pro pricing starts at $80/year.</p>\n<div class=\"alert alert-warning\"><p>Don&#8217;t forget, a secure website starts with <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/best-wordpress-hosting-guide/\">solid WordPress hosting</a>.</p>\n</div>\n<h3>3. <a title=\"Jetpack\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/jetpack/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Jetpack Security</a></h3>\n<p><a title=\"Jetpack\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/jetpack/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-540671\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/jetpack-security-protects-your-wordpress-sites.jpg\" alt=\"jetpack security protects your wordpress sites\" width=\"1116\" height=\"388\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/jetpack-security-protects-your-wordpress-sites.jpg 1116w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/jetpack-security-protects-your-wordpress-sites-300x104.jpg 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/jetpack-security-protects-your-wordpress-sites-768x267.jpg 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/jetpack-security-protects-your-wordpress-sites-1024x356.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1116px) 100vw, 1116px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Another popular all-in-one solution on our list of the best WordPress security plugins is <a title=\"Jetpack\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/jetpack/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Jetpack</a>. This well-known plugin lets you easily scan your website for security vulnerabilities and has over 5 million active installs.</p>\n<p><strong>Features:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Alerts you via email the moment it detects that your WordPress site is down</li>\n<li>Protects your site against brute force login attacks, spam, and harmful malware</li>\n<li>Site backups and 1-click restore</li>\n<li>Includes website design features and <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/best-marketing-automation-software/\">automated marketing</a> tools</li>\n<li>Automatic comment filtering</li>\n<li>Organized site activity and events dashboard</li>\n<li>Provides secure authentication via WordPress accounts</li>\n<li>Keeps your <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/best-free-wordpress-plugins-for-your-website/\">WordPress plugins</a> automatically updated</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong></p>\n<p>There&#8217;s a free version with very little functionality, so you&#8217;ll want the Premium version which starts at $9/month.</p>\n<h3>4. <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/wordfence/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Wordfence</a></h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/wordfence/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-540677\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/wordfence-security.png\" alt=\"wordfence security\" width=\"1116\" height=\"413\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/wordfence-security.png 1116w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/wordfence-security-300x111.png 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/wordfence-security-768x284.png 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/wordfence-security-1024x379.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1116px) 100vw, 1116px\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/wordfence/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Wordfence</a> is a free plugin that has some amazing security features that protects your WordPress site without you having to spend a cent.</p>\n<p><strong>Features:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Free to use for as many sites as you need</li>\n<li>Monitors visits and hack attempts in real time including origin, their IP address, the time of day, and time spent on your site</li>\n<li>Tracks and alerts you about breached password usage so you can create a new strong password immediately</li>\n<li>Protects from brute force attacks with limiting failed login attempts</li>\n<li>Runs on your own server instead of being cloud-based, so could slow your site</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong></p>\n<p>Wordfence is free.</p>\n<h3>5. <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/bulletproof-security/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">BulletProof Security</a></h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/bulletproof-security/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-540678\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/wordpress-user-security-vulnerabilities.png\" alt=\"wordpress user security vulnerabilities\" width=\"1116\" height=\"338\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/wordpress-user-security-vulnerabilities.png 1116w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/wordpress-user-security-vulnerabilities-300x91.png 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/wordpress-user-security-vulnerabilities-768x233.png 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/wordpress-user-security-vulnerabilities-1024x310.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1116px) 100vw, 1116px\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/bulletproof-security/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">BulletProof Security</a> is a WordPress security plugin that doesn&#8217;t look all that cool, but gets you some basic security features for free, so it&#8217;s worth being on the list.</p>\n<p><strong>Features:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>A somewhat easy-to-use setup wizard</li>\n<li>Malware scanning and firewalls</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-save-your-contact-form-data-in-wordpress-database/\">Database</a> backups</li>\n<li>Login protection</li>\n<li>Email notifications with security logs when a user gets locked out from failed login attempts</li>\n<li>Idle session logouts</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong></p>\n<p>BulletProof Security is free.</p>\n<h3>6. <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/all-in-one-wp-security-and-firewall/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">All In One WP Security &amp; Firewall</a></h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/all-in-one-wp-security-and-firewall/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-540681\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/best-wordpress-security-plugin-in-2019.png\" alt=\"best wordpress security plugin in 2019\" width=\"1114\" height=\"478\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/best-wordpress-security-plugin-in-2019.png 1114w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/best-wordpress-security-plugin-in-2019-300x129.png 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/best-wordpress-security-plugin-in-2019-768x330.png 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/best-wordpress-security-plugin-in-2019-1024x439.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1114px) 100vw, 1114px\" /></a></p>\n<p>It&#8217;s easy (and free) to use <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/all-in-one-wp-security-and-firewall/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">All In One WP Security &amp; Firewall</a> to apply most WordPress best practices for security to your <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/best-website-builder-for-small-business/\">small business website</a>. But the tool is pretty basic and not as beginner-friendly as the more well-known solutions.</p>\n<p><strong>Features:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Scanning for malicious patterns</li>\n<li>IP filtering to block specific people and geographical locations</li>\n<li>Login lockdowns after failed login attempts</li>\n<li>View a list of locked out users to unlock individuals in just a few clicks</li>\n<li>A password strength tool to allow you to generate appropriately strong passwords</li>\n<li>User account monitoring</li>\n<li>A website-level firewall (but does lack a DNS-level firewall)</li>\n<li>Lets you manually blacklist <a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/wp-tutorials/how-to-block-ip-addresses-in-wordpress/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">suspicious IP addresses</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong></p>\n<p>All In One WP Security &amp; Firewall is free.</p>\n<h3>7. <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/miniorange-2-factor-authentication/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Google Authenticator</a></h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/miniorange-2-factor-authentication/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-540688\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/google-authenticator.jpg\" alt=\"google authenticator\" width=\"1116\" height=\"523\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/google-authenticator.jpg 1116w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/google-authenticator-300x141.jpg 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/google-authenticator-768x360.jpg 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/google-authenticator-1024x480.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1116px) 100vw, 1116px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Setting up two-factor authentication for extra security is a really good idea to keep your website secure. <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/miniorange-2-factor-authentication/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Google Authenticator</a> lets you do just that. And it&#8217;s on our list since most security plugins don&#8217;t include this.</p>\n<p><strong>Features:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Adds an extra layer of security to your login</li>\n<li>Has a simple interface and is moderately easy-to-use</li>\n<li>Lets you pick which type of two-factor authentication you want to use</li>\n<li>Offers shortcodes so you can do things like use it on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-custom-login-form-for-improved-site-branding/\">custom login pages</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong></p>\n<p>Free.</p>\n<h3>The Best WordPress Security Plugin Winner</h3>\n<p>If you&#8217;re looking for a WordPress security plugin that has it all, there answers fairly obviously which you should choose.</p>\n<p>Our pick for the very best WordPress security plugin goes to <a title=\"Sucuri\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/sucuri/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Sucuri</a>, without a doubt. It comes with all the features you&#8217;ll need to protect your website, instead of just a few.</p>\n<p>This includes website scanning, DNS-level firewalls (not just website), and their own cloud-based server and CDN network.</p>\n<p>If you haven&#8217;t already, we recommend that you get started with <a title=\"Sucuri\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/sucuri/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Sucuri</a> as soon as possible. The Premium version isn&#8217;t free, but having a secure website&#8217;s going to save you a ton of potential costs and headaches in the event of a breach (Not to mention, peace of mind).</p>\n<h3>In Conclusion</h3>\n<p>And that&#8217;s it. Hopefully, this list of the best WordPress security plugins helped give you the info you need to find the best security tool for you.</p>\n<p>You may also really like our post with some awesome <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/proven-strategies-for-creating-secure-wordpress-forms/\">proven strategies for creating secure WordPress forms</a>.</p>\n<p>And if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Twitter</a> for more updates from our blog.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/best-wordpress-security-plugins/\">7 Best WordPress Security Plugins to Protect Your Website (2019)</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"https://wpforms.com/best-wordpress-security-plugins/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:4;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:76:\"\n		\n		\n				\n				\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n				\n								\n							\n		\n							\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:68:\"How to Create a File Upload Form in WordPress in 2019 (Step by Step)\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:66:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-file-upload-form-in-wordpress/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:75:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-file-upload-form-in-wordpress/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 19 Aug 2019 12:00:18 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:6:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"WordPress Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12:\"form entries\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:11:\"file upload\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:15:\"document upload\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:21:\"attach files to forms\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:5;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"conditional logic\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:27:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=1202\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:588:\"<p>Want to let your website visitors upload file attachments to your WordPress forms? Giving users the ability to add files and media to your site&#8217;s forms can make it way easier for you to collect the information you need. In this article, we’ll show you how to easily create a file upload form in WordPress. [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-file-upload-form-in-wordpress/\">How to Create a File Upload Form in WordPress in 2019 (Step by Step)</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12:\"Lisa Gennaro\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:34544:\"<p>Want to let your website visitors upload file attachments to your WordPress forms?</p>\n<p>Giving users the ability to add files and media to your site&#8217;s forms can make it way easier for you to collect the information you need.</p>\n<p>In this article, we’ll show you how to easily create a file upload form in WordPress.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a class=\"btn btn-block\" style=\"background-color: #659a17 !important; color: #fff !important; padding: 20px 25px !important; text-align: center; text-decoration: none; border-radius: 4px !important; -moz-border-radius: 4px !important; -webkit-border-radius: 4px !important; line-height: 48px; font-weight: bold;\" title=\"Click Here to Start Making Your File Upload Form Now\" href=\"http://www.wpforms.com/pricing/\">Click Here to Start Making Your File Upload Form Now</a></p>\n<p><iframe src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/zPVHHX99N_g?rel=0\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"><span data-mce-type=\"bookmark\" style=\"display: inline-block; width: 0px; overflow: hidden; line-height: 0;\" class=\"mce_SELRES_start\">﻿</span></iframe></p>\n<p>If you don’t like watching videos, or need more instructions, check out our step by step tutorial below.</p>\n<p>Here&#8217;s a table of contents for easy navigation of each step:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><a href=\"#step1\">Create Your File Upload Form in WordPress</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#step2\">Allow Multiple File Uploads</a> (Optional)</li>\n<li><a href=\"#step3\">Customize Your File Upload Form Settings</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#step4\">Configure Your File Upload Form’s Notifications</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#step5\">Configure Your File Upload Form’s Confirmations</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#step6\">Add Your File Upload Form to Your Website</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#step7\">View The Files</a></li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Why Use a File Upload Feature on Your WordPress Forms?</h3>\n<p>Depending on the type of information you want to collect on your form, using a file upload feature is one of the best ways to make it easier for you to get more info from your users quicker. Making forms easier to fill out helps <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-combat-order-form-abandonment-and-increase-your-sales/\">reduce your form abandonment rate</a> so your site can generate more revenue.</p>\n<p>You might need to add a file upload feature to your WordPress forms so you can collect different types of files and media from site visitors as they submit their form to you.</p>\n<p>Here are some of the most common times you might want to allow users to upload a file through your contact form:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-job-application-form-in-wordpress/\">Job application forms</a> so applicants can attach their resume files</li>\n<li>Pictures as image files for a contest or a <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/rafflecopter-alternatives-create-free-giveaway/\">giveaway</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-allow-users-to-submit-blog-posts-on-your-wordpress-site/\">User submitted content forms</a> so users can attach a blog post or image they want to share</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-request-a-quote-form-in-wordpress/\">Client services forms</a> so clients can attach their spreadsheet or project spec document</li>\n<li><a title=\"How to Create a Custom Support Ticket Form on WordPress With Zendesk\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-custom-support-ticket-form-on-wordpress-with-zendesk/\">Customer support forms</a> so customers can attach documents to provide additional information</li>\n<li>Audio clips for you to play back during your <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/best-wordpress-podcasting-plugins/\">podcast</a></li>\n<li>User-submitted videos on an <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-make-an-event-registration-form-in-wordpress/\">event registration form</a> so you have content to play at your event (great for <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/demo/wedding-invitation-rsvp-form-demo/\">weddings</a>, anniversaries, and <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/online-fundraising-ideas-for-nonprofits/\">fundraisers</a>.)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>And this is just the beginning.</p>\n<p>Luckily, the <a href=\"http://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a> plugin makes it easy for your site visitors to upload the following file types to your contact forms:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Documents</strong> (.doc, .xls, .ppt, and .pdf)</li>\n<li><strong>Images</strong> (.png, .gif, and .jpg)</li>\n<li><strong>Video</strong> (.mpg, .mov, and .wmv)</li>\n<li><strong>Audio</strong> (.wav, .mp3, and .mp4)</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"alert alert-info\"><p> Note: For <a href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/wordpress-security/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">WordPress security reasons</a>, the default file types that can be uploaded are limited. Here&#8217;s <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-allow-additional-file-upload-types/\">how to allow additional file upload types</a> to your forms.</p>\n</div>\n<p>Now let’s see how to add the file upload feature to your WordPress contact form.</p>\n<h3 id=\"step1\">Step 1: Create Your File Upload Form in WordPress</h3>\n<p>The first thing you’ll need to do is install and activate the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/pricing/\">WPForms plugin</a>. For more details, see this step by step guide on <a title=\"Step by step guide on How to Install a WordPress Plugin\" href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">how to install a plugin in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Next, go to <strong>WPForms » Add New</strong> to create a new form.</p>\n<p>Now, on the setup screen, name your form. Next, scroll down to the <strong>Additional Templates</strong> section and type &#8220;File Upload Form&#8221;, then click on it to open the template.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-538155\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/file-upload-form-template.png\" alt=\"file upload form template\" width=\"1116\" height=\"596\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/file-upload-form-template.png 1116w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/file-upload-form-template-300x160.png 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/file-upload-form-template-768x410.png 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/file-upload-form-template-1024x547.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1116px) 100vw, 1116px\" /></p>\n<div class=\"alert alert-success\"><p>Make sure you&#8217;ve already <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-install-and-use-the-form-templates-pack-addon/\">activated the Form Templates Pack Addon</a> to search for this form.</p>\n</div>\n<p>Now, WPForms will now populate a pre-built File Upload Form and display the drag and drop builder.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-538172\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/simple-form-with-file-upload-field.jpg\" alt=\"simple form with file upload field\" width=\"1116\" height=\"561\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/simple-form-with-file-upload-field.jpg 1116w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/simple-form-with-file-upload-field-300x151.jpg 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/simple-form-with-file-upload-field-768x386.jpg 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/simple-form-with-file-upload-field-1024x515.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1116px) 100vw, 1116px\" /></p>\n<p>Here, you can add additional fields to your contact form by dragging them from the left hand panel to the right hand panel.</p>\n<p>With the File Upload Form template, you’ll already have the <strong>Name</strong>, <strong>Email</strong>, <strong>Phone, File Upload</strong>, and <strong>Additional Comments</strong> fields.</p>\n<p>Click on any of the form fields to make changes. You can also click on a form field and drag it to rearrange the order on your contact form.</p>\n<p>You can also add the File Upload field to <strong>any WordPress form you create</strong>. Just drag the File Upload form field, found under <strong>Fancy Fields</strong>, from the left hand panel of the Form Editor to the right hand panel.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-538279\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/how-to-add-a-file-upload-field-to-a-contact-form.gif\" alt=\"how to add a file upload field to a contact form\" width=\"1116\" height=\"690\" /></p>\n<p>You can click on the File Upload field and change the:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Label —</strong> Name the form field so your site visitors know what it’s for.</li>\n<li><strong>Description — </strong>Add a description explaining details to users. For example, if you only want people to upload an image, tell them that.</li>\n<li><strong>Allowed File Extensions</strong> — If you want to restrict the types of files that can be uploaded to your WordPress form, put them here, each separated by a comma</li>\n<li><strong>Max File Size —</strong> Specify, in megabytes, the max size file you’ll allow users to upload. If you leave this blank, WPForms will allow a max of 128MB.</li>\n<li><strong>Required —</strong> If you want to require that users upload a file before they can submit their form, select this checkbox.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Wondering where these file uploads will be stored?</p>\n<p>By default, all files uploaded by users are stored in the WPForms folder inside the Uploads directory of your site. To make things easier, you can also store these files in your WordPress Media Library by selecting the <b>Store field in WordPress Media Library </b>checkbox under Advanced Options.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-538263\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/check-to-store-uploads-in-wordpress-media-library.jpg\" alt=\"check to store uploads in wordpress media library\" width=\"1116\" height=\"646\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/check-to-store-uploads-in-wordpress-media-library.jpg 1116w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/check-to-store-uploads-in-wordpress-media-library-300x174.jpg 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/check-to-store-uploads-in-wordpress-media-library-768x445.jpg 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/check-to-store-uploads-in-wordpress-media-library-1024x593.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1116px) 100vw, 1116px\" /></p>\n<p>Each file upload field allows users to upload one single file. To learn how to add multiple file uploads, read on. If just one file upload field works for you, you can skip the next step.</p>\n<h3 id=\"step2\">Step 2: Allow Multiple File Uploads (Optional)</h3>\n<p>You can add as many File Upload fields to your form as you want. To add multiple File Upload fields to your form, drag the field from the left hand panel onto your form.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-538319\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Multiple-File-Upload-Fields-onto-form.jpg\" alt=\"Multiple File Upload Fields onto form\" width=\"1116\" height=\"628\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Multiple-File-Upload-Fields-onto-form.jpg 1116w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Multiple-File-Upload-Fields-onto-form-300x169.jpg 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Multiple-File-Upload-Fields-onto-form-768x432.jpg 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Multiple-File-Upload-Fields-onto-form-1024x576.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1116px) 100vw, 1116px\" /></p>\n<p>But let&#8217;s say you want to add a bunch of File Upload fields — things might start to look a little cluttered.</p>\n<p>To make your form appear clutter free, you&#8217;ll want to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-clutter-free-forms-with-smart-logic/\">enable conditional logic</a> on the first File Upload field before you add those other fields. That way, those extra File Upload fields won&#8217;t show up on your form unless a user needs them.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-67046\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/wordpress-multiple-file-upload-form.gif\" alt=\"wordpress multiple file upload form\" width=\"562\" height=\"548\" /></p>\n<div class=\"alert alert-success\"><p>This trick makes the form look more organized and helps fight form fatigue, which can <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/simple-ways-to-design-your-forms-and-boost-conversions/\">help boost form conversions</a>.</p>\n</div>\n<p>To do this, drag a Dropdown field from the left-hand panel to your form, just above the file upload field. (This will work with any number of Upload File fields, but for the sake of this example we&#8217;ll do 3.)</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-538218\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/drag-dropdown-to-add-multiple-file-upload-fields.jpg\" alt=\"drag dropdown to add multiple file upload fields\" width=\"1116\" height=\"479\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/drag-dropdown-to-add-multiple-file-upload-fields.jpg 1116w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/drag-dropdown-to-add-multiple-file-upload-fields-300x129.jpg 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/drag-dropdown-to-add-multiple-file-upload-fields-768x330.jpg 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/drag-dropdown-to-add-multiple-file-upload-fields-1024x440.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1116px) 100vw, 1116px\" /></p>\n<p>Now click on the dropdown field to see the Field Options on the left panel and edit the Dropdown field label to say <strong>Number of Files to Upload </strong>and the Choices to say <strong>1</strong>, <strong>2</strong>, and <strong>3</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-538211\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/number-of-files-to-upload-dropdown.jpg\" alt=\"number of files to upload dropdown\" width=\"1116\" height=\"483\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/number-of-files-to-upload-dropdown.jpg 1116w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/number-of-files-to-upload-dropdown-300x130.jpg 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/number-of-files-to-upload-dropdown-768x332.jpg 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/number-of-files-to-upload-dropdown-1024x443.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1116px) 100vw, 1116px\" /></p>\n<p>After that, click on the File Upload field and in the options, scroll down to and expand the Conditionals tab in the left-hand panel. Then, select the checkmark for <strong>Enable conditional logic</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-223510\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Conditional-Logic.png\" alt=\"Conditional Logic\" width=\"562\" height=\"227\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Conditional-Logic.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Conditional-Logic-300x121.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Customize the conditional logic of the File Upload field just like the screenshot below:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-444029\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/upload-your-file.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/upload-your-file.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/upload-your-file-300x192.jpg 300w\" alt=\"upload your file\" width=\"562\" height=\"359\" /></p>\n<p>Keep in mind that new fields are added by clicking the Add new group button, which applies the OR logic. If you need more details about using the OR logic, read our guide on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-use-and-or-conditional-logic/\">how to use And OR conditional logic</a>.</p>\n<p>The next step is to duplicate this File Upload field.</p>\n<p>On your form, click on the duplicate icon on the right-hand side of the File Upload field.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-444198\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/duplicate-file-upload.png\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/duplicate-file-upload.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/duplicate-file-upload-300x152.png 300w\" alt=\"duplicate file upload\" width=\"562\" height=\"284\" /></p>\n<p>In the left-hand panel, change the label of the new File Upload field to <strong>Upload Your Second File</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-538324\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/rename-your-multiple-upload-fields-label.jpg\" alt=\"rename your multiple upload fields label\" width=\"1116\" height=\"594\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/rename-your-multiple-upload-fields-label.jpg 1116w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/rename-your-multiple-upload-fields-label-300x160.jpg 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/rename-your-multiple-upload-fields-label-768x409.jpg 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/rename-your-multiple-upload-fields-label-1024x545.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1116px) 100vw, 1116px\" /></p>\n<p>Now configure the conditional logic for this new field just like the screenshot below. The only change from the above step is that we removed the first action where it says the Number of Files to Upload is 1.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-67043\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/upload-second-file.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/upload-second-file.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/upload-second-file-300x193.jpg 300w\" alt=\"wordpress contact form multiple attachments\" width=\"562\" height=\"361\" /></p>\n<p>Now, duplicate the 2nd file upload field by clicking the icon and changing the label to <strong>Upload Your Third File</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-538327\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/name-your-file-upload-form-on-form.jpg\" alt=\"name your file upload form on form\" width=\"1116\" height=\"720\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/name-your-file-upload-form-on-form.jpg 1116w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/name-your-file-upload-form-on-form-300x194.jpg 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/name-your-file-upload-form-on-form-768x495.jpg 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/name-your-file-upload-form-on-form-1024x661.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1116px) 100vw, 1116px\" /></p>\n<p>Configure the conditional logic field just like the screenshot below. We’ll only keep the last field where it says the Number of Files to Upload is 3.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-444020\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/upload-third-file.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/upload-third-file.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/upload-third-file-300x192.jpg 300w\" alt=\"Upload third file\" width=\"562\" height=\"359\" /></p>\n<p>Once you are done customizing your form, click <strong>Save </strong>in the top right corner of your screen. You&#8217;ve just added multiple file upload fields to your form.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-538332\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/save-your-multiple-file-upload-form.jpg\" alt=\"save your multiple file upload form\" width=\"1116\" height=\"619\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/save-your-multiple-file-upload-form.jpg 1116w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/save-your-multiple-file-upload-form-300x166.jpg 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/save-your-multiple-file-upload-form-768x426.jpg 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/save-your-multiple-file-upload-form-1024x568.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1116px) 100vw, 1116px\" /></p>\n<p>So now that you have the right amount of file upload fields on your form (be it just 1 or multiple), you’re ready to configure your form’s settings.</p>\n<h3 id=\"step3\">Step 3: Customize Your File Upload Form Settings</h3>\n<p>To start, go to <strong>Settings</strong> » <strong>General</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-538333\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/File-Upload-Form-General-Settings-configurations.jpg\" alt=\"File Upload Form General Settings configurations\" width=\"1116\" height=\"668\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/File-Upload-Form-General-Settings-configurations.jpg 1116w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/File-Upload-Form-General-Settings-configurations-300x180.jpg 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/File-Upload-Form-General-Settings-configurations-768x460.jpg 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/File-Upload-Form-General-Settings-configurations-1024x613.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1116px) 100vw, 1116px\" /></p>\n<p>Here you can configure the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Form Name — </strong>Rename your form here if you want to.</li>\n<li><strong>Form Description — </strong>Give your form a description.</li>\n<li><strong>Submit Button Text —</strong> Customize the copy on the submit button.</li>\n<li><strong>Spam Prevention —</strong> <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-build-a-spam-free-contact-form-without-captcha/\">Enable the anti-spam honeypot feature</a> to prevent spambot submissions. This feature is automatically enabled on all WordPress forms. If you decide to use another form of spam prevention, unclick this option.</li>\n<li><strong>GDPR Enhancements —</strong> You can disable the storing of entry information and user details, such as IP addresses and user agents, in an effort to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-create-gdpr-compliant-forms/\">comply with GDPR requirements</a>. In addition, check out our step by step instructions on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-a-gdpr-agreement-field-to-your-sites-forms/\">how to add a GDPR agreement field to your simple contact form</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>And when you’re done, click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<h3 id=\"step4\">Step 4: Configure Your File Upload Form’s Notifications</h3>\n<p>Notifications are an excellent way to know when someone submits one of your file upload forms.</p>\n<p>And, unless you disable the notification feature, you’ll get an email notification whenever someone submits a form on your site.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-538336\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/set-up-notifications-on-file-upload-form.jpg\" alt=\"set up notifications on file upload form\" width=\"1116\" height=\"453\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/set-up-notifications-on-file-upload-form.jpg 1116w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/set-up-notifications-on-file-upload-form-300x122.jpg 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/set-up-notifications-on-file-upload-form-768x312.jpg 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/set-up-notifications-on-file-upload-form-1024x416.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1116px) 100vw, 1116px\" /></p>\n<p>To get an email message when someone completes your form, you’ll need to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-form-notification-wpforms/\">set up form notifications in WordPress</a> and provide your email address.</p>\n<p>Also, if you use <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-use-smart-tags-in-wpforms/\">smart tags</a>, you can send a personalized notification to your site visitors once they finish your form to let them know you received it. This assures users their form has gone through properly, along with their file upload.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-519747\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/how-to-use-smart-tags-in-notifications.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1116px) 100vw, 1116px\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/how-to-use-smart-tags-in-notifications.jpg 1116w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/how-to-use-smart-tags-in-notifications-300x173.jpg 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/how-to-use-smart-tags-in-notifications-768x444.jpg 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/how-to-use-smart-tags-in-notifications-1024x592.jpg 1024w\" alt=\"how to use smart tags in notifications\" width=\"1116\" height=\"645\" /></p>\n<p>For more on this, check out our step by step guide on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-multiple-form-notifications-in-wordpress-forms/\">how to send multiple form notifications in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>In addition, you have the option to easily brand your notification emails by adding your logo or any image you choose in the custom header image area. The logo/image you choose will show up at the top of email notifications like the WPForms logo below.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-211599\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header.jpg\" alt=\"Custom Email Header\" width=\"562\" height=\"314\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header-300x168.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<div class=\"alert alert-info\"><p> Note: Since file attachments can often <strong>hurt email deliverability</strong>, WPForms doesn&#8217;t attach your user&#8217;s files in notification emails. Instead, we send the file uploads via email as links.</p>\n</div>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-223516\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Notification-Email-Links.png\" alt=\"Notification Email Links\" width=\"562\" height=\"186\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Notification-Email-Links.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Notification-Email-Links-300x99.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<h3 id=\"step5\">Step 5: Configure Your File Upload Form’s Confirmations</h3>\n<p>Form confirmations are ways to take action immediately (and automatically) after your user has submitted information to your form. For extra help with this step, check out our tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-form-confirmation-wpforms/\">how to setup form confirmations</a>.</p>\n<p>There are 3 different kinds of confirmations in WPForms:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Message — </strong>This is the default confirmation type that appears after someone hits submit on your form, and it’s customizable. Check out our tips on ways to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/form-success-message-ideas-to-boost-customer-happiness/\">customize your confirmation message to boost your site visitors’ happiness</a>.</li>\n<li><strong>Display Page —</strong> Automatically send users to any page on your site like a <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/4-thank-you-page-examples-to-boost-customer-loyalty/\">thank you page</a></li>\n<li><strong>Redirect —</strong> Useful if you want to take the user to a different website or specialized URL for more complex development.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>So let’s see how to set up a simple form confirmation in WPForms so you can customize the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/form-success-message-ideas-to-boost-customer-happiness/\">success message</a> site visitors will see when they submit a form on your site.</p>\n<p>To start, click on the <strong>Confirmation</strong> tab in the Form Editor under <strong>Settings</strong>.</p>\n<p>Next, select the type of confirmation type you’d like to create. For this example, we’ll select <strong>Message</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-538344\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Form-Confirmation-Type-settings-1.jpg\" alt=\"Form Confirmation Type settings\" width=\"1116\" height=\"396\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Form-Confirmation-Type-settings-1.jpg 1116w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Form-Confirmation-Type-settings-1-300x106.jpg 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Form-Confirmation-Type-settings-1-768x273.jpg 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Form-Confirmation-Type-settings-1-1024x363.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1116px) 100vw, 1116px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, customize the confirmation message to your liking and click <strong>Save</strong> when you’re done.</p>\n<p>Now you’re ready to add your contact form to your website.</p>\n<h3 id=\"step6\">Step 6: Add Your File Upload Form to Your Website</h3>\n<p>After you’ve created your form, you need to add it to your WordPress website.</p>\n<p>WPForms lets you add your forms to multiple places on your website including your pages, blog posts, and <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-a-contact-form-in-wordpress-sidebar-widget/\">sidebar widgets</a>.</p>\n<p>Let’s take a look at the most common placement option: page/post embedding.</p>\n<p>To begin, create a new page or post in WordPress, or go to the update settings on an existing one. After that, click inside the first block (the blank area below your page title) and click on the Add WPForms icon.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-520176\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/embed-your-form-by-clicking-on-the-Add-WPForms-icon.jpg\" alt=\"embed your form by clicking on the Add WPForms icon\" width=\"1116\" height=\"399\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/embed-your-form-by-clicking-on-the-Add-WPForms-icon.jpg 1116w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/embed-your-form-by-clicking-on-the-Add-WPForms-icon-300x107.jpg 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/embed-your-form-by-clicking-on-the-Add-WPForms-icon-768x275.jpg 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/embed-your-form-by-clicking-on-the-Add-WPForms-icon-1024x366.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1116px) 100vw, 1116px\" /></p>\n<p>The WPForms widget will appear inside of your block. Click on the WPForms dropdown and pick the forms you’ve already created that you want to insert into your page. Select your file upload form.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-538367\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/add-your-file-upload-form-to-your-site.jpg\" alt=\"add your file upload form to your site\" width=\"1116\" height=\"488\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/add-your-file-upload-form-to-your-site.jpg 1116w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/add-your-file-upload-form-to-your-site-300x131.jpg 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/add-your-file-upload-form-to-your-site-768x336.jpg 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/add-your-file-upload-form-to-your-site-1024x448.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1116px) 100vw, 1116px\" /></p>\n<p>Next, click on the blue button in the top right that says either Publish or Update, so your form will appear on your website.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-520197 size-full\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/publish-or-update-your-page.jpg\" alt=\"publish or update your page and add a wordpress ajax contact form\" width=\"1116\" height=\"501\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/publish-or-update-your-page.jpg 1116w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/publish-or-update-your-page-300x135.jpg 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/publish-or-update-your-page-768x345.jpg 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/publish-or-update-your-page-1024x460.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1116px) 100vw, 1116px\" /></p>\n<p>That&#8217;s it! Your file upload form is now on your website.</p>\n<h3 id=\"step7\">Step 7: View The Files</h3>\n<p>WPForms stores each form submission as an entry. To view uploaded files, go to <strong>WPForms</strong> » <strong>Entries</strong>.</p>\n<p>From there, select the right form from the dropdown menu and click on <strong>View</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-538377\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/View-File-Upload-Entries.jpg\" alt=\"View File Upload Entries\" width=\"1116\" height=\"447\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/View-File-Upload-Entries.jpg 1116w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/View-File-Upload-Entries-300x120.jpg 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/View-File-Upload-Entries-768x308.jpg 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/View-File-Upload-Entries-1024x410.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1116px) 100vw, 1116px\" /></p>\n<p>Right click the file to download the file, or click to view it in your browser.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-538383\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/view-file-upload-entry-in-wpforms.jpg\" alt=\"view file upload entry in wpforms\" width=\"562\" height=\"331\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/view-file-upload-entry-in-wpforms.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/view-file-upload-entry-in-wpforms-300x177.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Better yet, you can use our <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/zapier-addon/\">Zapier addon</a>, to automatically save all file uploads to:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-wordpress-google-drive-upload-form/\">Google Drive</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-dropbox-upload-form-in-wordpress/\">Dropbox</a></li>\n<li>and many other cloud storage services</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>In Conclusion</h3>\n<p>And there you have it! You now know how to create a file upload form in WordPress.</p>\n<p>If you want to allow site visitors to upload files directly to your website, be sure to check out our helpful guide on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-file-upload-widget-in-wordpress/\">how to create a file upload widget in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And don’t forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-file-upload-form-in-wordpress/\">How to Create a File Upload Form in WordPress in 2019 (Step by Step)</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:71:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-file-upload-form-in-wordpress/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5